OpenTyrian2000
================================================================================

OpenTyrian2000 is an open-source port of the DOS game Tyrian. It is a fork of
OpenTyrian, with the end goal being to replicate the experience of Tyrian 2000
as closely as possible.

Tyrian is an arcade-style vertical scrolling shooter.  The story is set
in 20,031 where you play as Trent Hawkins, a skilled fighter-pilot employed
to fight MicroSol and save the galaxy.

Tyrian features a story mode, one- and two-player arcade modes, and networked
multiplayer.

== Additional Necessary Files ==================================================

OpenTyrian2000 requires the Tyrian 2000 data files, which have been released
as freeware:
  https://www.camanis.net/tyrian/tyrian2000.zip

== Keyboard Controls ===========================================================

alt-enter      -- toggle full-screen

arrow keys     -- ship movement
space          -- fire weapons
enter          -- toggle rear weapon mode
ctrl/alt       -- fire left/right sidekick

== Network Multiplayer =========================================================

Currently OpenTyrian2000 does not have an arena; as such, networked games must
be initiated manually via the command line simultaneously by both players.

syntax:
  opentyrian2000 --net HOSTNAME --net-player-name NAME --net-player-number NUM

where HOSTNAME is the IP address of your opponent, NUM is either 1 or 2
depending on which ship you intend to pilot, and NAME is your alias

OpenTyrian2000 uses UDP port 1333 for multiplayer, but in most cases players
will not need to open any ports because OpenTyrian2000 makes use of UDP hole
punching.

Note that Network play has not been tested for OpenTyrian2000.

== RetroWave OPL3 Express (FM Music on Real Hardware) ==========================

On Linux, OpenTyrian2000 can stream its music to a RetroWave OPL3 Express
board -- a real Yamaha YMF262 (OPL3) FM chip on a USB-serial bridge -- instead
of the built-in software emulator. Because Tyrian's own music driver produces
the OPL register writes, the result is the exact instruments, timing, and loop
points played on genuine FM hardware.

syntax:
  opentyrian2000 --retrowave=DEVICE

where DEVICE is the serial device for the board (typically ttyACM0). Use a
single dash (--retrowave=-) for a dry run that exercises the feature without
any hardware.

example:
  opentyrian2000 --retrowave=ttyACM0

The music plays through the board while sound effects continue to play on the
PC. Without the flag, the game uses the software emulator as usual.

You can also enable the board from inside the game, without the flag: open
Setup -> Sound and switch "RetroWave OPL3" to On. It can be toggled on and off
at any time, even while music is playing, and the choice is remembered between
runs (saved in opentyrian.cfg). The flag is still useful for selecting a
non-default device or for a dry run; when given, it also becomes the device the
in-game toggle uses.

Notes:
* The board runs at 2,000,000 baud; this is mandatory. A wrong baud rate fails
  silently (no sound or garbled output).
* You must have permission to access the serial device (on most distributions,
  add your user to the "dialout" group).
* This feature is Linux-only. A separate, self-contained standalone music
  player (a jukebox) for the board is available at:
    https://github.com/carlosbravoa/tyrian-retrowave-player

For convenience, the included play-tyrian.sh script wraps the flag:
  ./play-tyrian.sh            # game on the board (default ttyACM0)
  ./play-tyrian.sh ttyACM1    # game on a different device
  ./play-tyrian.sh -          # game with no board (normal emulated audio)

